The electron is excited from the valence band of PbI2 to its conduction band under UV irradiation (Eq. 2.1-18), which then transfers to O2 molecular to generate O2·− (Eq. 2.1-19). Finally, the highly reactive O2.− further reacts with PbI2 generating lead oxyiodide.

It’s reported that O2.− will capture an acid proton of the CH3NH3+ to generate hydroperoxyl radical (HO2·) once approaching the ammonium group (Eq. 2.1-21) [102, 103]. Subsequently, two different reaction mechanisms are proposed to express next degradation process of perovskite. The first one is that two HO2· interact to produce hydrogen peroxide (H2O2) under lights (Eq. 2.1-22). Ultimately, H2O2 reacts with Pb0 on the perovskite surface generating PbO or Pb(OH)2 (Eqs. 2.1-23, 2.1-24). It is worth noting that the formed PbO has an unexpected passivation effect, preventing the accumulation of anion vacancies and formation of Pb-Pb dimers, which can increase the open-circuit voltage (Voc) for inverted PSCs as exhibited in Fig. 4b. The second one demonstrates that HO2· radicals can dissociate into H2 and O2, and the remaining O2 can serve as a reactant again for the continuous degradation process (Eq. 2.1-25).2.1-21CH3NH3++O2∙-↔CH3NH2↑+HO2·\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
