As shown in Eqs. 2.2-7 and 2.2-8, the whole degradation reactions are the deprotonation process of CH3NH3+, and CH3NH3OH easily decomposes into CH3NH2 gas and H2O under heat. The decomposition of CH3NH3OH can promote the reaction (Eq. 2.2-7) to proceed forward continuously, which accelerates MAPbI3 degradation. It’s reported that MAPbI3 decomposes easily to form HI in humid conditions [94], which subsequently reacts with ZnO resulting in reduced electron mobility of ZnO and deteriorative chemical stability of PSCs. This neutralization reaction can be presented in the following reaction [127]:492HI+ZnO→ZnI2+H2O\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
